{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e4a0d065-1a19-4b35-9080-6dd687cc9e70","content":"You already have everything wired up. Here's how to use it:\n\n**Run tests in hot-reload mode:**\n\n```\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis starts a watch session — tests run immediately, and then **re-run automatically** every time you save a file change. No need to manually rebuild or re-run.\n\n**Your current issue:** `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` will fail because `IsValidEmail` only checks for non-empty strings, not for `@`. You can fix it, save the file, and hot-reload will re-run the tests instantly.\n\n**Workflow:**\n1. Start `dotnet test --hotreload` in one terminal\n2. Edit & save `EmailValidatorTests.cs` in another\n3. Tests re-run automatically on save — see results immediately\n4. Press `Ctrl+C` when done\n\nWould you like me to start a hot-reload session and fix the failing test?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed540dc3-fdc5-4153-9c19-31e8b6deb5d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to use the HotReload extension to iterate on fixes. Let me explain the workflow.\n\nThe package `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` is already referenced. The way to use it is with `dotnet test --hotreload`, which watches for file changes and re-runs tests automatically.\n\nLet me first run the tests to show the current failures, then explain the hot reload workflow.","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"F820:3BF41F:5AF3EBB:62D3F67:6A03376A"},"id":"e637e73f-9632-4fab-ab72-dc6a73c62fd0","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:21:46.995Z","parentId":"0e6f4428-9359-4655-8fe6-23aa2d652e02"}
